  "prompt": "If light has no mass, how can a solar sail be propelled?",
  "response": "Although light does not have mass, it possesses momentum. This is a consequence of the principles of quantum mechanics and electromagnetic theory. When photons\u2014the particles of light\u2014strike the solar sail, they transfer their momentum to the sail. \n\nThe transfer of momentum from photons to the sail generates a small but continuous pressure known as radiation pressure. Over time, this pressure can accelerate the sail, allowing it to gain speed and move through space. \n\nHere's a simplified version of the underlying physics: According to the equation \\( p = \\frac{E}{c} \\), where \\( p \\) is the momentum of a photon, \\( E \\) is its energy, and \\( c \\) is the speed of light, photons carry momentum proportional to their energy. When these photons reflect off or are absorbed by the solar sail, the momentum is transferred to the sail, providing a propulsive force.\n\nThis force is extremely gentle compared to conventional propulsion methods, but given the absence of friction in the vacuum of space and the continuous nature of solar radiation, a solar sail can gradually build up substantial velocity.",
